				\begin{document}$$ {\text{Recurrent Outbreak Index}} = \frac{{A_{1} }}{{\mathop \sum \nolimits_{i = 1}^{N} A_{i} }} $$\end{document}Recurrent Outbreak Index=A1∑i=1NAiwhere Ai denotes the maximum cumulative number of infected cases in ith wave, and N denotes the number of epidemic waves, which ranges from 0 to 1. The Recurrent outbreak index depends on the proportion of the maximum number of infected cases in the first wave. We considered two extreme cases. The first is if there is only one wave of epidemic in a region, in which case we closer to 1. The other is if there are multiple waves of epidemic in a region, and each wave of epidemic situation causes a similar number of confirmed cases, in this case the indicator would be closer to 0.
